title: The Original French Market Restaurant and Bar
text: Worse dining experience of my life. Definitely- ‚≠êÔ∏è if I could. Service was bad, restroom was bad, & the food was so horrible I was sick immediately after eating just a few bites!! I‚Äôd rather burn my $100+ spent there than eat there again. 1st time visiting  New Orleans & this experience completely ruined it for me & my family. We walked in & the vibe wasn‚Äôt friendly at all. I should have known to trust my gut feeling. The server coldly handed us menus & left. I was debating if we should leave cuz he didn‚Äôt come back for like 15mins, but I wanted to give him another chance. He quickly took our orders & left with a cold expression. My son ordered dirty rice & he said we don‚Äôt have that. So I‚Äôm like ok maybe he‚Äôs having a bad day it‚Äôs whatever. Wrong!! While waiting for our food, I went to use the restroom. Doors were broken for both stalls. Toilet paper roll on the ground & one didn‚Äôt even have toilet paper. There was no soap or paper towels. It was so sketchy, I decided to hold myself until we got to another bathroom. When we finally got our food it didn‚Äôt look bad but after tasting the food I felt sick right away. And wasn‚Äôt sure if it was just me. But nope!! Tried the jambalaya rice & it tasted like sour partially uncooked rice. Horrible!! Took a few bites of my seafood boiled. The potato & corn textured seemed ok but the flavor was very strange. You‚Äôd think since Louisiana is know for their seafood boils it‚Äôll be at least edible. I don‚Äôt know what seasoning they put in their seafood boiled, but ü§¢ü§Æü§Æü§Æ. I ate one shrimp & it tasted like I was eating raw stanky fish. I had a few other people tried it & said it was bad too. I immediately decided we shouldn‚Äôt eat anymore of our food. I didn‚Äôt don‚Äôt want us to get food poisoning since we were on a road trip & had many stops to go yet. Our bill was $100+ for the most nastiest food ever. My husband was so kind he still left a tip despite how horrible everything was. I literally was trying hard not to vomit as we were walking out of the restaurant. I barely made it out before vomiting outside & on the way to the public restroom a few blocks away. It was so bad I couldn‚Äôt get rid of that nasty taste in my mouth. I drank half a bottle of coke & ate ice cream to cleanse my palate. Finally stopped my urges to vomit. My hands stank like raw fish even after washing my hands 20 times at 5 different bathrooms. I have never left a online review for a restaurant before, but I want to warn people about how horrible this experience was. It‚Äôs so sad that there was absolutely nothing good about this restaurant. Try it at your own risk.

title: The Original French Market Restaurant and Bar

My dinner guests were just as pleased with their food. Only ding was at the beginning we ordered dessert to come after our meal, but it never came and not on the bill so we paid and didn‚Äôt bring it up, next time we will try it.

title: Swoop's Supper Club | NOLA
text:
I cannot say enough fabulous things about this beautiful venue and Ms. Linda Novak, its proprietress and event coordinator. I approached Ms. Novak with less than one (1) months‚Äô notice and an unusual request to propose to my girlfriend there after discovering that the Swoop-Duggins House was open for private events ‚Äì years ago, my girlfriend (now fianc√©e) and I had our very first date ‚ÄúCellar Door‚Äù (bar operated by previous tenant/owner), but I had been advised that it had been shut down in Hurricane Ida. I was so thrilled to see that Ms. Novak was now hosting events in the space again and invited myself over for a walk-through as soon as I got in contact with her. Despite my paltry budget (much less than she normally agrees to rent the space for); an insanely complicated plan for a proposal (I had to lead my girlfriend in through a side entrance that she‚Äôd not recognize, then ask Ms. Novak to herd in in 30 guests to the front room within a 5-minute window before bringing my fianc√©e out to propose to her on the balcony where Ms. Novak had provided a perfect ‚Äúhiding spot‚Äù under a tablecloth for my friend to photograph the proposal, after which I brought her down the courtyard steps where she coordinated the timing of my friend‚Äôs dad‚Äôs trumpet-playing); an ever-changing number of guests and menu items (from 12 to 35 and then back down to an eventual 30); and two highly-invested mothers participating in the surprise, Ms. Novak graciously and seamlessly pulled off an engagement event that most people that I was crazy for even attempting.

Ms. Novak spent weeks working with me and my friends and family to ensure that everything went right in this multi-layered plan that likely would take the award for ‚Äúvenue‚Äôs worst nightmare event‚Äù ‚Äì from coordinating walk-throughs in the week leading up to the event, to actually playing a part in the surprise herself (she went so far as to make fake signage and decorations for another ‚Äúevent‚Äù that was to take place that night; and put her acting skills to work to make my charade more believable), she was beyond incredible. All of my guests asked whether she was a wedding coordinator that we could hire, given her flawless facilitation of the entire evening ‚Äì if only she were available to handle my wedding! Needless to say, my fianc√©e was thrilled and said yes. We now hope to plan an engagement party or wedding event at the Swoop-Duggins House next year.

As for the venue itself, Ms. Novak has done an impeccable job of decorating the space down to the very last detail ‚Äì it is New Orleans through and through, and captures the essence of the Crescent City through its d√©cor and ambiance. Cocktails and appetizers were of course fabulous, as well. No way to go wrong with this venue and Ms. Novak. Thank you.

title: Namaste nola
text:
We live near by this restaurant and decided to have a dinner.
We travel and eat out lots. Also being a Hindu vegetarian can write lots about this place.
This restaurant had many new dishes which we don‚Äôt find in other Indian restaurants in NOLA.
It took real long for our order and the portions were very small. The menu is glorified and all necessary accomplishments not served with appetizers or meals.
We order the Paruppu wada for $10. Two small pieces of hard wada served without any chutney. Please don‚Äôt order this appetizer as it was too dry and no taste at all.
We also ordered the Gobi Manchurian was tiny portion and dry without main ingredients like garlic.
The main reason of our visit was to try the Gutti Vankaya, a fancy name for the eggplant curry.
The peanut based curry was great but eggplants were not cooked to the perfection. Literally we ate curry sauce with rice.
This restaurant is located in the CBD and great for the tourists who don‚Äôt care about their money.
I would not recommend this restaurant for locals.

text:
Poor service and rude owner..

When my group arrived here I opened the front door without stepping in in order to ask if we could be seated outside.  The host rudely yelled at me to put a mask on. My intention was to sit outside to avoid digging out a mask but rather then simply tell me I could go ahead and have a seat the host wouldn't answer me until I put one on. He then told me I could sit at 2 tables. Half of my group was already there and we took a seat at one table.  The server walked by our table twice but did not greet us. The rest of my group arrived and took a seat at the other table.  They had a separate server that brought them water immediately.  My table continued to wait so I went to ask if we had a server coming.  A server told me he would be right with us. I apologized but told him my boyfriend needed to get to the airport soon.  He brought waters to our table.  At that time he took our food and drink order. The second table had their food order taken about 5 minutes after us. All of their food came out more than 10 minutes before ours. After waiting a total of 45 minutes after giving our order my boyfriend went in to ask them to box our food and pay the bill as we no longer had time to eat.  It seemed that the slow service was purposeful as we were overlooked several times.

I was also not impressed with the food.  Small portions and over priced.

Once learning of my poor experience I was contacted by the owner.  Rather then apologize for the bad experience he berated and name called me for writing the review.

I do not recommend this restaurant.

title: 14 Parishes Jamaican Restaurant at Algiers Point
text:
14Parishes has 2 locations, I've been to both! The Oak Street location is a Caribbean vibe! Start out with the amazing food, drinks (the Rum punch got me every time, so yummy!), and service in the restaurant area. Once you wrap it up, they have a lounge upstairs called the Hummingbird on the weekend! Dope drinks and rooftop vibes... Talk about the perfect spot for an all evening into night date night spot or a time on the town with your girls!

They have a more family-friendly location - Algiers Point - much more spacious, but offers the same great quality of good, drinks, and vibes! There isn't a lounge at this location, but it doesn't take anything away from it.

Whichever your mood, check out either of the locations!

I didn't take many pics, but I found these ones - a drink pic and some artwork hanging in the lounge!

title: 8 Block | Kitchen & Bar
text:
If you're seeking an exceptional dining experience in New Orleans, the ‚Äú8 Block Bar‚Äù at the Hyatt hotel is a must-visit destination. While the food itself is undoubtedly delicious, it's Grace's outstanding service that truly sets this place apart. From the moment you enter, Grace's warm and welcoming presence puts you at ease.

Grace's attentiveness is truly unparalleled. Even amidst the bustling atmosphere, she always finds the time to check on her guests, ensuring that every need is met with a genuine smile and friendly demeanor. Her ability to remember regular patrons and greet them familiarly is a testament to her dedication to providing a personalized experience.

What makes Grace truly remarkable is her passion for her craft. She takes immense pride in her work, and it shows in the way she effortlessly navigates the busy restaurant, ensuring that each guest feels valued and attended to. Whether you're a first-time visitor or a regular, Grace's infectious positive energy and excellent customer service will leave a lasting impression.

The Hyatt hotel is truly fortunate to have an employee like Grace, who embodies the essence of hospitality. Her commitment to her job and her ability to create a welcoming atmosphere make the 8 Block restaurant a must-visit for anyone seeking an exceptional dining experience in New Orleans. Oh, I asked her for a recommendation, as i was asking for a Calamari and she suggested a popcorn shrimp and the burger. It was fantastic and superb! I highly recommend giving it a try.

I did not get the omelette and waffle I ordered the first time and had to complete a second card. I waited over 30 minutes before getting the omelette and waffle that I ordered. My family waited over an hour to get theirs. The manager apologized for the omelette and waffle station and fully refunded our money. I do not recommend the omelette and waffle station. title: Sneaky Pickle & Bar Brine
text:
With a name like Sneaky Pickle, we thought the menu would be full of pickle plates. We were wrong, but it's still worth visiting. It's more than worth visiting. It's among the best food we had while spending six days in New Orleans. Dining around 5:30 p.m. on a Wednesday in April, here's our experience.

1) Food: Everything we ate was delicious starting with the oysters and ending with the wagyu burger, which my seven-year-old daughter enjoyed too. The sunchokes are unique and worth ordering. My mother-in-law loved the squid ink pasta and my wife really enjoyed the buffalo tofu lettuce wraps (what they are known for).

2) Drink: Their menu includes cocktails, beer, wine, and more. I ordered a rainbow sherbet sour ale. My wife liked their brine drink for a savory option.

3) Service: From the hostess to the server, everyone was kind, efficient, and welcoming. Our food was perfectly timed.

4) Space: It's beautiful with a large indoor dining room and a bar. There are two unisex restrooms in the back near the stairs to the second level, which I assumed was for staff only.

5) Area: We found free street parking nearby. Located inside Bywater, it's a great neighborhood to walk around after dinner, finding little houses and parks. For dessert, we walked to nearby Big O's Original Popsicle Doorbell.

title: Sneaky Pickle & Bar Brine

text: Breakfast wings! With maple syrup and sausage crumbles. That‚Äôs how you want to start your day. Seriously, great service, chill vibe, and yummy food.

title: District All Day Delicious
text:
Oh. My. God. If you‚Äôre thinking about going - do it. Immediately.

We originally went as I was looking for a brunch restaurant that could accommodate my dad (he‚Äôs in a wheelchair/service dog), and we were also looking for something that prioritizes their food quality. Look, I like NOLA but I was tired of the standard, touristy, overpriced options. The pancakes in the Google listing + ability to make a reservation made the choice easy for us.

When we arrived we were greeted by the co-owner and immediately felt welcomed. It was an awesome surprise to also find that they offered delicious coffee options and we promptly ordered. We ordered an array of coffee (honey cinnamon latte, honey lavender latte, and iced vanilla bean logged - all delicious!) and for food the Lemon Ricotta pancakes, BLT, and Hot Chicken & Honey Biscuit. The pancakes are INCREDIBLE. My mother - who LOVES pancakes - was obsessed with them. The BLT was great and the hot chicken was so-so, but was made up by the delicious potatoes served as a side.

Upon leaving we immediately planned another day to come for breakfast for more pancakes. Upon our second visit we got more pancakes (the lemon + the Pigs in a Blanket), coffees, and the GM Plate. We were all satisfied and became curious on how they created the most perfect pancakes recipe. I‚Äôm not kidding - I hate pancakes and will now dream of them.

If you‚Äôre considering this place just do yourself a favor and go. Sure, the more ‚Äúpopular‚Äù choice is on the corner of the same strip, but it doesn‚Äôt compare to this place. Truly. The service, the atmosphere, and the menu are fantastic. Amazing!!

P.S. they have doughnuts/pastries and house-made ice cream as well. We never ordered them, but they all looked fantastic and had great flavor combos.

title: District All Day Delicious
text: I wish I didn't have to give any stars. The food is bland, and the grits come with cheese. They dried out the bacon to gerky status, and all they offer in the form of cheese is cheddar. Who puts cheddar cheese on eggs? Don't waste your time

title: District All Day Delicious

We had a great time here and love the casual atmosphere and happy people that works here. Highly recommend!

title: District All Day Delicious
text:
Today was my friends and I last full day in NOLA‚Ä¶ I chose a restaurant on the same block for brunch, but when we arrived it was a 40 min wait. District was right on the corner, so we walked over to see if the wait time was shorter.

We were seated right away!
And in many ways I‚Äôm really glad the original spot didn‚Äôt work out‚Ä¶ because what a gem this establishment is. The two chefs in the kitchen I‚Äôd like to give a kudos too! Because by far this was the most delicious meal I had this entire trip!

When our food arrived there was no salt and pepper‚Ä¶ and guess what! I didn‚Äôt need it! Everything perfectly seasoned and cooked!

When I return back to Louisiana, this will NOW BE MY GO TO SPOT!

text: I wouldn't know how the food was because I was completely ignored. I went this evening for a bite, asked the host if I could sit at the bar and eat, he said yes. FInally a woman came up to me said hi and I asked if I could see a menu, she gave me one and proceeded to clean up around me, helped several other patrons at the bar, I sat there another 5-7min with NOTHING in front of me, not even offered a water! I finally just left after I saw 4 men being attended to, they already had drinks and water! Then I saw another man being offered a refill on his wine to seats awsy from me, I was thinking this cannot be real, do they not see me? There was three people behind the bar. This was offensive and will spread the word not to bother going if your a woman eating alone, plain and simple rude and uncalled for. I was there early in the evening the dinning room wasn't even a little busy. In total I waited almost 15 min to see if anyone would come and apologize and take my order. Don't waste your time!

title: Rib Room
text:
Went for dinner on a Monday night with coworkers, we‚Äôre all also staying at the hotel. Reservation at 7:15, sat around 7:20. No one came by the table to even take appetizer orders for at least 20 minutes. A guy eventually came over with bread in that 20 mins and we asked him for our server.

I speak for the whole table when I say the overall service was subpar for the price, we each spent $50-100 to only have water filled once, if that, and a hefty wait in between ordering, receiving food, and checks. My check was also incorrect which ended up costing an extra 15 mins to fix that. Food was ok, but it‚Äôs not worth the languishing service attitude and several mistakes on the orders.

All in all, we were out a little after 9 and exhausted as we have to work each day starting at 6am. Likely won‚Äôt be back unless it‚Äôs room service or bar food.

Edit: I genuinely didn‚Äôt expect this review to carry any weight in the world at all, not even in the slightest. I assumed it would get lost within all reviews never to be seen again. But within hours of me posting the hotel set out to make it right which is crazy. Also, I didn‚Äôt realize the hotel is so involved with the restaurant or even cared what went on in it! Anyway, I gave a couple stars back for their trouble to do so, thank you!

title: LUFU NOLA
text: We very much enjoyed this restaurant tonight! The flavors! We had the pani poori  and kunthal fry for starters. The pani poori is a delicate crunch and refreshing explosion in your mouth. We also ordered the tandoori lamb burra. The lamb chops were succulent and the mint chutney was the perfect accompaniment. The Manso Kosha (goat) was fall apart tender and the sauce was a nice ratio of sweet with a spicy kick. Don't forget to get the Naan to finish off that sauce. We also ordered the chicken biryani that was flavorful and the chicken was tender. For drinks we tried the spicy Rita with tamarind and a gin cocktail with peach, both very tasty. I am so thankful for our server (I wish I remembered his name). He was very knowledgeable and gave great recommendations on what to order and tips of how to eat the different food with their chutnies. I love the ambiance of the restaurant and it was a great birthday meal. We also got sat next to the window where we could view the kitchen, and I thought that was kinda cool. I wish we could try more, but unfortunately, we can only eat so much.

Not to mention the bread was wet. They said it was just their liquid butter. I would never be writing this review but when the waitress presented a bill for $80, I decided to post my comments. The side dish of pasta was okay but overall we were disappointed.

title: Caf√© Fleur De Lis
text:
I came to this corner cafe for breakfast. I ordered shrimp and grits plus a biscuit. The shrimps tasted fresh. Honestly I hated grits but because shrimp and grits seemed to be a famous New Orleans dish. I felt it necessary to give it a try.

It turned out that the grits mixed well with the shrimp sauce and the melty cheese, which tasted a bit salty. The biscuit was a separate order, but I am glad that I ordered it because if I ate the grit alone it would be too salty for me. By the way, the biscuit was quite buttery but not fluffy enough.

I went there before 9 am on Saturday. No need to wait. When I left, however, people were already forming a line outside.

title: The Pelican Club
text:
We had reservations for four at 8pm. Place was packed. Our table wasn't ready for about 30 minutes but we were eventually seated. We ordered drinks and the $6 bread service immediately. We all did either the three-course or four-course dinners which were easy and priced well. I added an A' La Carte Mixed Lettuce & Arugula "Wedge" salad which wasn't the best. The lettuce was a bit warm and wilted like they had it under a heat lamp. My daughter had the Little Gem Caesar Salad which was extremely too fishy from the anchovies. They took it back. We did the Creamy Shrimp Bisque, Escargots En Croute (very good), Pelican Club Baked Oysters, two of the Braised Pork Shanks, Louisiana Cioppino - In Its Own Pot, two of the Decadent Chocolate Cakes, and the White Chocolate Bread Pudding.
Everything was decent but they were too busy and our only server just couldn't keep up. They really need some support servers for drinks, bread, and table clearing. It is the main reason for 3-Stars instead of 5! There are too many places in NOLA to eat, so we probably won't be back!

title: The Pelican Club

Cannot wait to come back.

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text:
Went there for dinner with a childhood friend last week.

We started with an order of 4 of the appetizers intending to do a tapas kind of thing for dinner. (Everything but the pate).

The server was adamant that we had to select an entree. We explained that we wanted to look at the menu some more.

Truth be told, I had looked at the menu and honestly nothing spoke to me. I'm a bit of a simpleton and prefer simple food cooked well. The offerings here are a lot of things, simple isn't one of them.

After a bit of a stand off, the server departed in a huff with our order.

The appetizers were good, but like everything else there is just too much going on for me. Too many flavors competing on your tongue.

Eventually we ordered gumbo and a caprese salad.

The gumbo was simply okay. I had had a significantly better cup of gumbo at a popular restaurant in bucktown the night before. In addition there was a very slight fishy taste to the gumbo telling me it wasn't the freshest thing in the world.

The caprese salad was fine except for the balsamic vinegar, which was the refined version that is sweet. Typically the refined is put on ice cream and such. Don't know if it really works on a salad, definitely not for me.

I guess this all would have been ok if the bill for 3 people wasn't $300.

Not recommended.

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text:
PATRIOTS SHOULD NOT FREQUENT THIS ESTABLISHMENT !
Unbelievable. We were shown to our table and the gentleman server introduced himself. After exchanging the usual pleasantries he took the liberty of giving us his political opinions regarding the upcoming election without any hesitation and consideration to our opinions.
We don‚Äôt think it is the right thing to do as an employee to spout your political opinions on others while working.
Suffice it to say we simply walked out.
We were there to enjoy a nice meal not have a political debate.

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text: Completely exceptional dining experience. I am so glad we found this little gem. The menu is set daily, based on what is fresh. And it is made to perfection. Our server, Rene, was extremely kind, and engaging. I truly didn‚Äôt expect such a good experience, considering the atmosphere - candidly it‚Äôs very ~meh~. But I considered that part of its charm. Also, the prices are totally fair and reasonable. Don‚Äôt sleep on this place. It‚Äôs so so so good.

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text: One of my favorite restaurants!

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text: The atmosphere is relaxed yet elegant in a house. Excellent attention and knowledgeable service. The gumbo was excellent which is why we went but the Traiteur Fish and cassoulet were equally as delicious!

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text:
I ordered duck gumbo and asked multiple questions. What kind of duck? Is the sausage peeled?  The manager did not know the answer to either question.

The gumbo soup was bitter.  The duck was chewy--normal. I informed Gabrielle I found the soup bitter. She did not respond to my query until I asked twice, and she said the roux is very dark but not burnt.

If a gumbo tastes bitter the roux is burned.

The bread and butter was delicious.

The club soda was very refreshing, but the glass of Pinot Noir average.

The menu changes daily or weekly; the staff was discussing the day's menu for a salad carefully.

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text: Our server was friendly and very pleasant. The food was fabulous and our meal was served at a nice pace for a beautiful evening.

title: Gabrielle Restaurant
text: The dining space is small, the neighborhood is questionable and parking is a bit janky. But with that said, the charm, coziness and customer service balanced things out. There was a host of items on the menu that were premade with pork, which was a little limiting. But I really enjoyed the BBQ shrimp pie which was simultaneously sweet and savory. My favorite of all the dishes tried. They have an interesting take on bread pudding, where they add apples. I wasn't a huge fan. But overall, the food and cocktails were good and the space was really inviting.

title: Dahla
text: This is a really good locally owned Thai restaurant just a few blocks outside the French Quarter. I got the Crab Rangoon and the gyoza as appetizers, and they were amazing! For dessert, I loved the Umi cheesecake so much I got a second slice. I also found the chandeliers and the detailed mural made the space feel classy but still casual. The service was also very good. I will definitely be back.

text:

title: Dahla

title: Dahla
text:
I was already a fan of this spot, but after my experience tonight, they have earned a customer for life! The place is well-decorated, the food is consistently delicious and affordable, but the service is where they really impressed me this visit.

I ordered a dish for take out and paid extra for glass noodles, which wasn‚Äôt an issue. When I got home from picking up my order, I realized there was an error and I didn‚Äôt receive the upcharged noodles. Just as I was about to call the restaurant, they called me first!!

They were super apologetic and made it right. I have never had that level of customer service with a takeout order before.

I frequent this restaurant for lunch and dinner, but I will always come back now due to that simple act of service. Thank you!

title: Dahla
text:
Ok so this place has been on my radar for a while ‚Ä¶ last night, we had birthday dinner reservations on the OTHER side of St Charles which we couldn‚Äôt get to because of parade timing. We took a chance that we might get in at Dahla if we were lucky?

Not only did we get an immediate table during Mardi Gras weekend, but we got fast, wonderful service, awesome drinks, and surprisingly quick, perfect food.

Panang curry was rich with perfect heat. Pad Thai was equally delicious but the TOFU!! Maybe the best I‚Äôve had in New Orleans.

Thank you for such a great experience! Can‚Äôt wait to go back.

title: Mena's Palace
text:
We were staying at the Wyndam Hotel (April 4,5,6,7,8), and it is literally around the corner! We asked the front desk staff and two of them said Mena's (in unison?!?!?!).  200 St Chartres.  Ok, so they liked Mena's. We also asked a pedicab driver - again Mena!  So, we tried it. So glad we found it early in our vacation. We were there for all breakfasts from then on. Great food, great employees - felt like home. Unfortunately, we didn't discover their lunch menu until the last day (try the muffaletta - I wanted to take some home!) It was so soft and flavorful.  Lots of options too.  While it didn't affect us - they have a bar, too!
The servers were very positive and friendly! The two we used (and enjoyed) were Dymond and Jamayra. Mena only does breakfast/lunch and that is fine. However, we would have lived there if they did dinner too!
Not fancy-shmansy but clean, friendly and very good food. We will be back!
Lou R

title: Yawdi Jamaican Restaurant/ Food supplies
text: I can‚Äôt eat at Yawdi anymore. Every time I‚Äôm in there they are out of oxtail and items on the menu (at the restaurant). Today I saw them at an event and ran up to ask if the oxtail was in stock. It was. I now know why. It was a $25 plate. I was happy to support. At checkout the girl adds 18% tip to my purchase and tried to just skip through to have me sign. I'm staring at the handheld machine thinking, "did she just put 18% on my order and not at least tell me??" They get my food together and then she realizes she didn‚Äôt add my side of plantains I ordered. So it's going to be another $5. I watch her the second time and sure enough i see her pause and then quickly select the 18% again. üòë So then i ask her. She said a bunch stuff that makes absolutely no sense "it's going to charge you $5 so im fixing it‚Ä¶" Sure. I finally look at her realizing she's not disclosing how shes pricing all of this and isn't going to tell me the truth. I get home, eat my side of plantains, they're what I wanted. I open up my plate and I'm dumbfounded. Half the plate is rice. I tried it, it was ok. I thought it was meant to be a side, but it was most of the styrofoam container. I try the mac n cheese. Meh‚Ä¶it was not worth the dairy issues to eat it (for me). My mom and I do make really good mac though, so I'm bougie lol. But the OXTAIL wad an afterthought! I got three tiny chunks of bone in the sides section. It was about 4 bites of meat‚Äînot even 4 oz. ü§Ø The four bites were delicious, but it was four bites for like almost $30!? I dont even feel like trying to eat the rest. So I'm done. I've tried to reason and revisit this place but it's always some humbug. Now I'm sitting here mad because I need to an actual plate of food more than just rice. üòë I hate to leave a bad review but this needs be said. I‚Äôm a small business vendor so I don‚Äôt leave bad reviews lightly.

title: Criollo Restaurant
text: All of my senses were OVERWHELMED with pleasure at Criollo's Jazz Brunch! The service and food was superb Michelin level quality. The live jazz band kept me entertained as I was coursed out. The chef elevated the fried green tomatoes and chicken biscuit to an award winning level. The chicken biscuit was smothered in jalape√±o's, scallions and the best rue I have ever tasted so I sent my compliments to the chef. Every delectable bite forced my eyes shut so I could deeply enjoy the freshness, flavor and texture. While I was enjoying coffee the chef sent complimentary Rosemary & Lemon Custard Madeline's. It was an innovative way to approach this classic pastry. My only critique is the custard on top was so good I wanted more. Very light, fresh, and balanced melody of flavors. The consistency was reminiscent of a fusion between a scone and puff pastry. You can tell the French invited fries by how well the fries here complimented every dish. It was such a phenomenal experience, I found myself making reservations for the next day halfway through brunch and I am happy to say the food, service and entertainment are consistently great here. The fancy French atmosphere at Hotel Monteleone was fit for a Queen and the bathroom attendant cleaned the stall prior to each guests use. This is a must try spot in The French Quarter.

title: Criollo Restaurant
text: The beignets were ABSOLUTELY BETTER than cafe du monde!!! And the seafood gumbo was the best i‚Äôve had during my 3 days!

title: Criollo Restaurant
text: Great food and very friendly staff. Outstanding service.

title: Criollo Restaurant
text: This place is very accommodating, friendly and warm. Alexander was our helper and he was the best- so is Roy. We had a family post graduation dinner here and it is unforgettable. The manager even came to check on us. Alexander took time talking to us about the menu and even directed where to go for a walk after. The ambiance is very classy. I would recommend this place especially to people who want to learn about the local foods and how they prepare them.

title: St. Roch Market
text:
This is such a unique location in New Orleans. Picture the French Market but nicer, cleaner, and enclosed.

There are several restaurants within St. Roch that serve Cuban, Mexican, Japanese, and Cajun food (more than that). Everything I've had here is delicious (albeit a little expensive, especially if you get a drink).

Besides food, St. Roch is also a great studying location. The building has plenty of windows and tables, making it perfect for work. There's also a wonderful coffee shop as well that serves delicious drinks and pastries.

Also, the service here is wonderful. Although each booth has its own employees (they're okay) the stars of the show are the St. Roch "waiters." They constantly clean the tables and make sure you have iced, filtered water along with your meal.

If you want to go to a place that'll make you question your decision-making skills, this is the place!

title: St. Roch Market
text: The concept is a great idea, the food I got was so so... next time  I'm in New Orleans  I  will try some different food from this place...

title: Broussards Restaurant & Courtyard
text:
the restaurant is incredibly beautiful.   we were the first people in the dining room at 515 on Monday.   We ordered drinks, an appetizer, and 2 entrees.   The waitress recommended the porkchop, describing it as  "juicy".  My wife's meal was good.  My porkchop was overcooked and dry.  I ate about 30% of it, hoping "juicy" would be in the middle somewhere.   I mentioned that to the other waiter (every table has 2) and he laughed like I was telling a joke.

The subtle complaint is lost on this place.   if you get poor quality like I did, I would recommend just sending it back.   Another oddity, they don't clear plates between courses.   The man literally shoved my plate to the other side of the table spilling the silverware on the tablecloth in the process.

The bread pudding is delicious, though it was a little abrupt to have the check tossed on the table 60 seconds after the dessert was served.

text: This was one of the best meals I‚Äôve ever had,  not just in New Orleans but anywhere! I enjoyed it so much, that I came twice during my visit. My all time favorite is the Massaman curry with lamb, but the crawfish green curry and soft-shell crab pad Thai are close seconds.  If you are in the area, do not skip this place! The smell will catch your attention from the street, and once seated the elevated hospitality of Misty, Greg, and Nathan will ensure the experience of eating here is one you‚Äôll remember forever. title: Dian Xin
text:
Visiting the quarter and wanted some Chinese, so this was one of the first spots we kept seeing show up online.

The best two items were: The crab/crawfish dumplings, fantastic. And, the saut√©ed green beans. They are crisp and hot, but still tender inside. A bit too much sauce for me, though.

Runner ups: The steamed pork buns. Stuffed with a good amount of meat inside, they were super fresh and soft. The basil popcorn chicken. So crispety and crunchy, and served piping hot. Egg rolls were different than traditional ones. Not as much of a cronch on them, but still good.

The char siu pork was sadly probably my least favorite item. It needs more char, and less of whatever sauce they're using, they need more of that traditional red sauce (see photos).

Service is super friendly, fast, and attentive.

text:
Excellent service and food. We were pleasantly surprised after seeing other reviews at how wonderful the service was from our arrival through the end of our meal. Our server Luka was outstanding, providing thoughtful recommendations, as well as prompt and friendly service. He went over and above to get our beverages just how we wanted. For food, The charbroiled oysters were a standout- the best out of 3 different spots we‚Äôve tried them in this trip. We also enjoyed the pesto pasta dish, which had a nice balance of fresh and spicy flavors. And the turkey club was good, too.

I didn‚Äôt love the blaring TVs everywhere theme. It seems like having the gigantic multiple screen spread over the bar would be plenty for those who are there to watch sports in a group setting. We asked to have the one at our table turned off, and Luka was able to get the volume off, but having the screen playing corny commercials the whole time felt invasive. I‚Äôm still going with 5 stars because the service was 10 star caliber!

We would rather have brunch at any of the many other restaurants in the area for the same price. Saint John is a little cheaper with a much better caliber of food and experience. title: The Court of Two Sisters
text:

We had the Crab Cake and the Louisiana Crawfish & Shrimp Pasta. Both were extremely good! To finish we got the Bananas Foster which is prepared table side.

The Court of Two Sisters is a must if you have a desire to enjoy a meal in a garden setting. The service is top quality and the food is great.

title: The Court of Two Sisters
text:
I understand that when you offer a buffet the food needs to be prepared for a basic pallet but  some things were bland, overcooked or undercooked. The prime rib was overdone, the wild rice was undercooked, and the garlic mashed potatoes lacked salt and garlic however the omelet/egg station was excellent. My husband loved that they freshly poached eggs for the eggs Benedict and the hollandaise was homemade. The peel and eat shrimp, grits and creamed spinach were excellent and the service was good. Our server Derrick was really nice and I always appreciate someone with a smile. We also tried their version of a hurricane called a "The  Flamingo" its one of the best drinks we've had in New Orleans and I highly recommend trying it. I think we drank three each during lunch.
This is also a beautiful setting to have some day drinks at but be aware there are a lot of little birds around so don't leave your food unattended. The house band was also good and not too loud. We would eat here again.

title: Meals From the Heart Cafe
text: I was visiting New Orleans for a business trip April 15-17. I came across Meals From The Heart on TikTok. I decided to try this restaurant because the reviews on TikTok were good. Upon arrival I met the cashier. Her service was OK. I ordered the crabcake, a small gumbo and a cold pressed orange juice. I was really excited about the food as I haven‚Äôt had any good vegan food since I visited New Orleans. A lot of the restaurants that I wanted to visit were closed or had closed early. I first tried the gumbo and it was OK. I wish that it had more rice, vegetables and mushrooms. I don‚Äôt know if this is the correct way to describe it, but it was very loose and not very thick. The next thing I tried was the crabcake and it was OK. If it were not for the sauce I don‚Äôt think it would‚Äôve been that great. The orange juice however was pretty good. Overall with tip I spent about $40. The crabcake alone was $10. My suggestion is that For $10 you should get two crabcakes and the gumbo should be thicker maybe add some more vegetables, mushrooms and rice I left feeling unsatisfied. I was disappointed with the portion of food I received for the amount of money I spent. Although I am very grateful to have found one vegan restaurant during my trip.

I would most definitely come back to try that out or any of the other delicious looking options. They had a variety of food options with a lot of traditional New Orleans fares as well like red beans, okra gumbo and beignets. So I would say this is a great place to try some true NOLA foods. title: Blue Bayou Restaurant and Oyster Bar
text: We visited Blue Bayou later in the evening when we were out looking for an after dinner drink and some dessert. The atmosphere looked inviting, and a quick review of their sidewalk menu lead us to believe we had found the place.  There weren‚Äôt many people in the restaurant but the bartender looked like a ball of frenetic energy. She was running around and asked us if we had been waited on yet, we said no and then she rushed away. A few minutes later, an engaging server stopped by and took our order. We ordered two desserts and four drinks. The desserts arrived long before the drinks and were not as shown in the menu. The menu describes a large slice of banana fosters cheesecake topped with sliced bananas and whipped cream. We received a sliver of cheesecake with no bananas. The sliver wasn‚Äôt enough for two. Three of our four drinks arrived after we finished our desserts, one drink was MIA. Mine was supposed to have rum in it but I couldn‚Äôt taste any. I chalked that up to the nutmeg on top. Another drink was supposed to be a lemon drop and tasted like water and lemon. We knew, with 100% certainty that the drinks were heavily watered down when the fourth drink finally arrived. It was supposed to be one of their signature drinks, an Old Fashioned. What is typically a beautiful dark caramel liquid, with a small amount of ice, dark cherry, bitters, sugar or simple syrup and maybe an orange slice came out looking like a slightly beige glass of water with a maraschino cherry and filled to the brim with ice. It was so watered down that the bourbon was hardly detectable. No simple syrup or sugar was used. And the bitters that make an OF so special were missing as well. Our server was great, I really wish I remembered his name!  The music was interesting‚Ä¶ but we won‚Äôt be going back.

title: Blue Bayou Restaurant and Oyster Bar
Blue Bayou Restaurant and Oyster Bar
text:
My wife and I had a terrible experience with this establishment. There were warning signs early that we ignored, so ultimately we could have avoided our lackluster dining experience.
We walked up to the hostess station and were greeted by a young woman who was in the middle of dealing with her false eyelashes falling off, so we waited while she dealt with her personal emergency. She was very nice and apologetic for it, I'm sure that she was quite embarrassed. The restaurant wasn't busy at the moment, maybe a total of 5 tables, this is a large restaurant. We waited roughly 5 minutes for our server to greet us, placed a drink order along with an appetizer order. The server brought our waters and said our drinks would be out shortly. We started hearing the kitchen yelling for service for several minutes, the wait staff were elsewhere at this point, and then we started seeing the kitchen staff attempting to bring out the orders themselves. They were obviously confused as the whole each item was supposed to go to, but they were making an attempt. Kudos to the back of house for making an effort. They did make some negative comments about their coworkers as they were returning to the kitchen, we were sat by the kitchen so got to be the audience.

We received our appetizer after a few minutes of it being passed around from person to person before finally making it's way to our server.
We waited 10 minutes for our drinks to finally make it to our table, not promising for such a large business that wasn't busy. We had ordered the crab cake appetizer, it was very small, good flavor and quite a lot of crab for what looks like a 3 ounce cake. I would have been a little happier for either a little more or little less expensive ($26), this is obviously in the heart of the tourist trap but this was egregious even with that in mind. My entree was delivered within minutes of the drinks and appetizer. I had ordered the Blue Bayou shrimp Poboy, I was surprised by how much shrimp was on the sandwich especially after how small the appetizer was. My food sat on the table untouched for nearly 10 minutes before our server came to check on us, finding my wife's entree had never been delivered. She went back to the kitchen to check, came back out to apologize and said that the missing entree would be delivered shortly. We waited another 15 minutes for my wife's shrimp and grits entree, my food was now cold and we began eating our dinner.
The Poboy was not bad, even for being cold, it lacked some of the bold flavor you would expect for a Creole BBQ shrimp poboy but was more than edible. The side of fries were very good, large portions of shrimp and fries.
My wife said the shrimp and grits were okay, not as good as the same dish from the Ruby Slipper I had ordered for breakfast on the same day for significantly less money. But she did enjoy the dish well enough.

The server did offer to comp a glass of wine to make amends for the poor timing of the service, we declined and finished our meal. We found the service at this restaurant to be seriously lacking compared to the other establishments we visited during our visit to the city. The prices were on par with higher end establishments, but it falls short of the competition in my experience. We didn't walk in with any expectations, but we left disappointed with the overall experience.  We would not return or recommend this restaurant. There are too many great places to enjoy good food and drink in this city, avoid this lackluster tourist trap.

**Also of note - this restaurant charges an additional 3% on card payments, and they're a cashless business. So expect all prices to be an additional 3%***

title: Dooky Chase Restaurant
text:
My husband and I were determined to have dinner here. Dooky Chase is only open for dinner on Friday & Saturday evenings and reservations were hard to get. I ended up calling there one afternoon right before they closed to make our reservation.

The inside of the restaurant is beautifully elegant, filled with gorgeous art. I had the fried chicken, which was delicious and just a bit spicy, and my husband had the stuffed jumbo shrimp. We ended up taking a box home. I recommend the rum punch as a cocktail. We finished off with some piping hot praline bread pudding.

The service was excellent and we were glad we got an opportunity to eat here.

title: Dooky Chase Restaurant
text:
After years of trying, we finally coordinated the timing of a visit to New Orleans that allowed a reservation for lunch at Dooky Chase. It also coincided with a monster rain storm that saw crazy street flooding with 6 inches per hour falling from the sky and submerging the streets.

The staff could not have been more welcoming, nor the dining room more elegant. I absolutely had to try the Creole gumbo, and it's now my favorite gumbo in New Orleans (sorry, Mr. B"s).  The meal was excellent, the service above and beyond. And with suggested wine pairing were spot on.

When it was time to leave, the water was up to the steps leading out to the street. The hostess insisted we leave through the back door where the water had not yet reached and led us through the kitchen, a fascinating side trip by itself. She then waited with us in the parking lot under our Uber arrived. Talk about commitment to customer service!

It was a wonderful experience on an historically bad weather day.

title: Dooky Chase Restaurant
text: AVOID this restaurant!!! One of worst dining experiences ever. We had reservation at 05:30 for 5 people and when arrived we were told to head to bar had a mix up for our table. No one ever came to get us after said would just be a few minutes . We headed back up to hostess desk after waiting for amount of time we were told. We stood another couple minutes in the line near hostess desk and were finally called. The hostess desk is very unorganized and whole reservation system is very poorly managed. We headed to our table at 05:50 we didn‚Äôt get waited on until 06:20 and this was after several waiters walked by and the large table behind us sat after us and got waited on before us . We waited over an hour for our food and we had to have someone from our table go to host desk and inquire about order because our waitress disappeared. She then came by table after inquiring about order and told our ticket was up next it was an hour and ten minutes to get four entrees. I understand delays happen but your staff shows no care or concern . We talked to ‚Äúkitchen manager ‚Äú and host at desk and they showed no concern. No manager ever came by table to check in which is so bizarre . After stating how long waited for food the waitress said can offer dessert on the house. After one of us said just take their one entree off before we got food, she had to realize we waited too long. At this point we just wanted to leave it was ridiculous it took that long as other people that sat after us and only had 2-5 people in party and had over 5 tables  around us that got food before us. title: Galatoire's
text:
While strolling the heart of Bourbon Street, stride into a world of refined elegance at Galatoire's in New Orleans, where over 100 years of tradition converge with exquisite culinary craftsmanship. From the moment you enter through its French doors, you are enveloped in an atmosphere of sophistication and old-world charm. You are treated to a dining experience that is both traditional and refined, a true celebration of Louisiana's rich culinary heritage*. Impeccable service and classic Creole dishes await each bite a testament to the restaurant's commitment to excellence. It is a place where tradition meets innovation and where every meal is an unforgettable celebration of food, family, and community.

üç≤What I Tasted: The appetizer quartet showcased flavors from the indulgent crab maison to the crispy fried oysters. For the main course, fresh local saut√©ed fish adorned with seasonal crawfish Etouff√©e. The fish had a delicate yet rich flavor profile that melted in your mouth. The optional lemon caper beurre blanc sauce, with champagne, was the perfect complement to the fish, adding a velvety smoothness and subtle acidity and saltiness to each bite.

üí° Standout Feature: their unwavering dedication to preserving Creole traditions while infusing modern flair sets it apart. With every bite, you are transported to a bygone era of refined dining, where the vibrant culture of Louisiana comes to life.

‚ö†Ô∏è What Was Mid: While some may find the classic decor and attentive service charming, others may perceive it as slightly rigid or stuffy. It has all the qualities of rigid service, former attire, and feeling of exclusive clientele but without the real upscale elegance of refined dining elements However, whether the ambiance suits your taste is subjective and may depend on your dining preference.

*If you are a guy do not forget your jacket it is one of the few places in town that does require one after 5:00

title: Galatoire's
text:
This restaurant is definitely overhyped in New Orleans. Securing a reservation can be tough, which might give you the impression that everyone is clamoring to dine at Galatoire's. They enforce a formal dress code, and if you arrive without a jacket, they'll provide you with one if you want to sit in the main dining area. You'll quickly notice that the clientele tends to be on the older side.
Once you're seated and handed the menu, the waiters are quite focused on upselling you on various items. We opted for a crab salad to start, and honestly, it was presented in the most disappointing manner I've ever seen from a high-end restaurant. Our main courses, shrimp creole and crab sardou with spinach and artichoke, also lacked in presentation. While the taste was decent, it fell short of gourmet standards, especially given the price.
Service wasn't particularly efficient either; we observed waiters wandering around aimlessly. I'm not trying to criticize the place unfairly, but I truly don't believe it deserves to be ranked among the city's top restaurants. If you adjust your expectations accordingly, you may be able to avoid disappointment.

title: Galatoire's
text:
3rd visit. First two were amazing, and this time definitely not......

We prefer to not dress up too much and sit in the bar area, and have always loved every minute of it. This time we were told the bar area was full (even though there were clearly empty tables) so we were led into the secondary dining area and it's a whole different world and not for us. We didn't order wine and my wife wasn't too hungry so only ordered a salad and a side dish, and the waitress didn't seem to be happy about that and didn't pay much attention to us. Also the bar area is calm and laid back but both dining are as loud as a high school cafeteria and for some reason no one even tries to keep their voices down. We could clearly identify voices from multiple tables across the room and it seemed to be normal. When my drink was gone she took it away and didn't ask if I wanted another. So no dessert for us, we ate and left. Would go back again, and put our foot down for the bar area, but not sure how much leverage we'll have with a $50 deposit on our reservation.......

title: Galatoire's
text: A disappointing experience all around. The service is inattentive and rests on their notoriety assuming everyone will just agree it‚Äôs amazing. We arrived for a 6:30 reservation and was told as we started to order that there was no crab available. Over half of their menu are crab based dishes. This seems to be a problem with sourcing and ensuring the restaurant is properly prepared to serve what‚Äôs on their menu. We ordered the oysters Rockefeller and were very disappointed. There were no bread crumbs to be found on these oysters, the spinach looked like someone dumped a can of goopy spinach on top, and they over baked the dish. I could bounce my fork off of the stiff spinach goop on top of the oyster. I waited for my waitress to ask how it was as we only ate two of them‚Ä¶ she didn‚Äôt ask, and when she came to remove them, I informed her they were not good. She said, ‚ÄúI‚Äôll tell my boss‚Äù and carried them away. The ‚Äúboss‚Äù did not come to check with us and they indeed did charge for them. The main entres were mediocre and nothing to rave about. The service was ‚Äúbarely check the box‚Äù and a bit arrogant. Sadly, another overrated restaurant that rests on their past reputation. Don‚Äôt fall for it‚Ä¶ go find a lovely restaurant where they care about your experience.

title: Gianna Restaurant
text:
We walked in and sat at the bar because we were told the earliest seat we could get was over 1.5hr wait. It‚Äôs a Thurs night and we had no reservation so that‚Äôs not unusual- sign of a good restaurant, right?

At no point while we were there (almost til 8) did the restaurant even approach 2/3 full. Maybe a bunch of no shows? Or maybe it‚Äôs because the food just wasn‚Äôt good.

We started with the Provola sausage appetizer that was OK, but tasted kind of lemony - maybe the oregano was just way too heavy? But the sausage definitely didn‚Äôt stand out.

Then, after over a 25 min wait including us promoting the bartender to check, I had spaghetti fra diavolo. I expect a little spice in fra diavolo, but it was pure black pepper that I tasted. No tomato, chili, basil or lemon. The shrimp were rubbery to boot. Did not finish. And we had paesano potatoes. The Parmesan was past the point of melting to nearly burnt on, there was no rosemary or garlic flavor. It didn‚Äôt even taste like it had salt or pepper (maybe they ran out after the spaghetti‚Ä¶).

And to top it off, the service was not good. We had to prompt them to check for our food after we had been sitting for 25 min. Generally when sitting at the bar, the bartender will check on your drinks to see if you like them - esp when one has an empty cocktail glass. Not tonight at Gianna.

title: Trenasse
text:
Went previously for dinner a couple years ago and was really good.  Crawfish pie was amazing.

Went a few weeks ago for lunch and was not the same experience. Crawfish pie was ok, but crust was overcooked.  Also got oysters and had to send back and explain why to the waitress (cheese was so burnt it was black).

So, overall a solid spot to eat with nice atmosphere, but for the prices got to ding them for the lunch performance.

title: Trenasse
text:
Okay y'all, when I tell you I had my doubts.... They were absolutely unfounded.

This place was AMAZING. Everything, the food, service, ambiance, bathroom, and cocktails.

I brought my brunch bunch in this last Saturday for the bottomless deal. We had a 12 top and never wanted for a thing!

I was actually SURPRISED at how effective the mimos were, despite the fact that they mixed them for you (not my favorite thing and I had called ahead and was told they specifically DID NOT DO THIS, but it all turned out to be just fine).

Everything everyone ate was DEVINE. Not a single complaint to be had by my party of 12. That's quite a feat. I was having so much fun I didn't even get pictures of the food!

I had the boudin has, delicious but the star of the show (besides of course our AMAZING, SWEET, PATIENT, BUTT KICKING server, Tara ?I think)) was the crawfish pie. It was more like a pot pie, with poached eggs. Absolutely DELICIOUS. And sooooo my charbroiled oysters to choose from!

At some point there was gumbo and beignets too... Mmmm!

This place is right around the corner from my job and I will definitely be back! Thanks Trenasse!

2024 update- I have been back multiple times for both brunch and dinner and honestly everything is just as amazing every time. The service, the food, the ambiance... It just all hits even the price points! Don't sleep on the oyster log!!!

title: Felix's Restaurant & Oyster Bar
text: We went to the Felix‚Äôs at the French Quarter the evening of 4/16/24. Not having been back to New Orleans for a few years, I was excited to return for the char grilled oysters. We have been multiple times in the past and the food has been great, and staff so friendly but unfortunately not this time. When arriving, there was an African American female hostess with glasses. Multiple tables were open but she told us we would have to wait for a 2 top table to be cleaned. We asked why we couldn‚Äôt sit at a 4 top, when she had seated other parties with 2 people at the 4 top tables. She smirked and refused to provide us with respond, instead just ignoring us. We made the decision to go elsewhere and when telling her same, she again just smirked as though she was proud of her actions. When we told the couple behind us of what happened, they also left the location and the hostess continued to smirk about her decision to treat us as she had. I made the mistake of calling the Lakefront location, instead of the French Quarter, and spoke to the supervisor. She was appalled by the fact an employee of Felix‚Äôs would treat customers as we were treated. She said the situation was totally mishandled and if it had been her location, she would have marched up front and made the situation right. She also recommended I write this review to advise the owner of what had happened. We have since left a voicemail for management, with no response but this type of customer service will keep me from returning. Instead, we went to Acme around the corner where the staff was friendly, food was great, service was efficient, and we weren‚Äôt discriminated against as we were by that hostess. Highly recommend Acme if you are in the area and looking for oysters and/or po boys! This situation was totally uncalled for by an employee in customer service when the restaurant wasn‚Äôt busy, and we were willing, paying customers.

title: Felix's Restaurant & Oyster Bar
text: It's a toss-up between Felix's and Acme for my favorite Oyster bar in New Orleans. I first went to Felix's decades ago, and I go to both when in New Orleans. At Felix's, I always start with a half dozen each of raw, char-broiled, and Oysters Bienville, and if still hungry, I get a Shrimp Po-boy. Oyster prices have increased greatly since Covid, but you get what you pay for, and Felix's oysters, for me, are as good as they come.

text:
A++ for atmosphere here at Brennan's! What an awesome looking place. So much detail with hand painted murals everywhere, colorful wall panels and moulding, and really cool lighting. A functioning player piano welcomes you as you enter the main lounge. So cool!

I would recommend this place for ambiance alone but it turns out the service is fantastic and so is the food! This was one of the most fun restaurants we visited in New Orleans and it's definitely worth the trip in my opinion.

Pro Tip: Get seated in the lounge if you want to listen to the player piano. Sit in the main dining room for the really fancy wall art. Both sections are awesome!

The atmosphere was up scale and unique and added to the overall experience. Our server was very nice but the service was a bit slow. Overall we were there for 2 hours for brunch. However, we would still definitely recommend!

title: Brennan's
text: Well, what can I say about this old school standard! My father ate here in the late 50's and was forever changed by the eggs husard and the home of bananas foster! 60 years later, I did the same! Go and tell your grandkids about it!

The shrimp was ultra tender and big chunks of crab in it. The ooey gooey raspberry buttercake was all of its words. Damn good. Lawrence and his apprentice with the red hair were amazing. Shout out to them and their amazing service.

text:
On my 3rd visit to Mulantes I switched up my usual fried shrimp and fish order to a cheeseburger and fries! Hoping to experience more wonderful food from this restaurant I patiently awaited my order . I asked the waitress to ensure my burger was well done with no pink . After receiving the order I first noticed how small the burger was for $19.00 . I was the size of a small kids burger but more than that the burger appeared to be gray which caused me to break a piece of the  meat off and smell it! The meat had a spoiled small as if it was expired meat or left out for a long period of time . I asked my friends to also confirm the stink that the meat had and all 3 of us agreed that something wasn‚Äôt right with the meat. I asked the waitress to send it back and to take it off of my bill . Because I

I was charged $6.00 for a hand full of fries ! The manager walked right by our table and never apologised or said anything to me . I will never eat there again and started to scream out to the other guest Not to eat the Meat . I was told they will

title: Luke
text: The shrimp and grits here is amazing. The cheesy jalapeno grits made the dish with flavourful shrimp and sauce atop. The bone marrow was a bit disappointing in flavours. It needs some seasoning and refinement. My partner got the Bouillabaisse which looked great but we feel the dish needs rice instead of bread to really get that sauce. To end, we got the bread pudding which was delicious. I wish I stopped the waiter before he poured the entire serving of caramel sauce on top as I tend to prefer my desserts less sweet. Nonetheless it was great and the added pecans was a nice touch. I also tried the blackberry cocktail which was disappointing. The cocktail tasted alright but it was not cold enough and clearly had not been chilled or shaken with ice. I would skip the cocktails here. Service was friendly and attentive. The place is lacking AC (or maybe it was off) so it can get a touch warm.

title: Luke
text:
Luke is a great little French restaurant situated in the Central Business District just south of French Quarter. My wife and I went for lunch and we decided to go all in and try a couple of traditional French items we had never had.

We ordered three items from the "To Share" section of the menu. Here's what we ordered:
1) Pat√™ of Louisiana Rabbit and Chicken Liver
2) Crispy Brussels Sprouts
3) Escargot & Bone Marrow
4) Saison du Pont (beer from Belgium)

I have to say, neither my wife nor myself enjoyed the pat√™. To be fair, this stuff looked legit. I'm confident this was excellent quality and it just turns out we aren't pat√™ people. The sprouts were fantastic and I was a huge fan of the accompanying sweet pepper sauce. Bone marrow is always amazing, and this was no exception. We enjoyed the escargot and it paired quite well with the marrow and the grilled bread served with the dish.

Service was excellent, food was great quality, and we were in and out pretty quickly. Definitely recommended if authentic French food is what you're looking for.

title: Luke
text: Amazing service, delicious high-quality food, and a great location slightly away from all the hustle and bustle. This is a fantastic restaurant! title: M & J Soul Food Restaurant
text:
Stopped in with the hubby on the way to Maryland from Houston. We wanted to find a local place that was off the beaten path.

We were thoroughly impressed with our meal. I had the fried porkchops with candied yams and potato salad. The porkchops were humongous compared to what I'm used to and they were fried perfectly. The candied yams and mashed potato salad were both addictive.

The hubby had the seafood pasta, fried fish, and jambalaya. The pasta sauce was flavorful, but he was sad there wasn't more crab that was noticeable. However he did love the jambalaya and wished he had gotten a double helping of it instead of a salad.

Definitely worth a visit for comfort food that's a great price for the portion size.

title: Russell's Marina Grill
text:
Located in the heart of Lakeview, Russell‚Äôs Marina Diner stands as a cherished beacon of New Orleans‚Äô rich culinary tradition.

Since its inception in 1985, this diner has carved out a niche for itself as the go-to destination for exceptional breakfasts, weaving itself into the fabric of the city‚Äôs dining scene.

With a menu that spans the gamut from indulgent fried chicken and waffles to a diverse array of egg specialties, Russell‚Äôs caters to a broad spectrum of tastes.

Not forgetting the health-conscious, the diner also offers lighter fare such as eggwhite omelets and sweet potato pancakes, ensuring that every patron leaves satisfied.

The dining experience is further enhanced by the option to enjoy your meal either inside the diner‚Äôs cozy interior, at the counter where the local vibe thrives, in their inviting dining room, or outside on the pet-friendly patio, making it perfect for every occasion.

During my visit, I decided to try the legendary Egg Saints #33‚Äîa daring concoction that perfectly embodies New Orleans‚Äô flair for culinary innovation.

This dish features a grilled biscuit topped with alligator sausage, grilled tomatoes, poached eggs, and smothered in homemade country gravy.

Each component of the dish harmonizes to create a breakfast experience that is both unique and profoundly satisfying.

From the moment I stepped inside, I was greeted with the diner‚Äôs unmistakable local charm, enhanced by the friendly service that made me feel right at home.

The ambiance, a blend of the cozy and the communal, set the perfect stage for what was to be an unforgettable meal.

The Premier League playing softly in the background added a touch of camaraderie, reminiscent of a neighborhood caf√© where everyone is welcome.

The highlight of my visit was, without a doubt, the food.

The Egg Saints #33 was a revelation, transforming the classic eggs Benedict into a dish that captivated my palate and left me pondering the culinary prowess behind it.

Every bite was a testament to Russell‚Äôs commitment to quality and innovation, making it clear why this diner holds a special place in the hearts of New Orleans‚Äô residents and visitors alike.

In a city lauded for its vibrant food scene, claiming the title of "best breakfast" is no small feat.

Yet, as I left Russell‚Äôs Marina Diner, I was already yearning to return and dive deeper into their menu.

This hidden gem is an absolute must-visit for anyone looking to experience the soul of New Orleans through its food, served with a side of unmatched hospitality.

title: Burger King
text: I'm not a true fan of Burger King; however, around 11 p.m., I stopped at the location on Bullard. Immediately, I was greeted and was told they were only accepting cash. I responded by saying, "No, problem. " The cashier asked me for my order in the most polite way with that New Orleans feel. You know, "baby" at the end of a sentence. She gave a new meaning to customer service because she was articulate, direct, and polite. She told me exactly where to park and wait, and she brought my food to the car in a timely fashion (Oh, and the impossible whopper was good). Now that's what I'm talking about, baby!

title: Deanie's Restaurant & Bar
text:
This is my favorite local spot in New Orleans.  It is not frivolous and is tucked away from the hustle and bustle of the tourist areas.  The food is absolutely the best.  Amazing Southern flavors, spicy, savory, and smoky.  Their prices are amazing, and they have multiple daily specials that change daily, so you always get something different if you want.

I ordered the red beans and rice and a side of mustard greens.  The beans and rice were smoky and packed full of flavor.  The greens were perfectly seasoned, and the pot liquor..... Oh my lawd!!! SO good!!

This place is a must visit when you're here! Great hospitality from the staff, amazing food, and the serve Red Cream Soda.  Where else can you get this Southern staple!!!!  Simply the best!

title: Deanie's Restaurant & Bar
